Earlier this month wholesale gas prices reached their highest levels in two years as markets reacted to the crisis in Ukraine, prompting fears fuel could be affected as a result.

The cost of crude oil also rose – driven by fears that Russia, which is a major producer, might be hit by trade sanctions.

A spokesman for the AA told the Daily Mirror: ‘You don’t get much more unstable than Russia invading another country.'

The good news for motorists has also been offset by a real-terms plunge in earnings which has pushed wages back to 2002 levels, according to the AA Fuel Price Report.

In an effort to support drivers, George Osborne announced in his Budget this week another fuel duty freeze.

